reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 30, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Cool, Quiet, Great Value
reviews.reviewText: Cools my i7-14000k great, with a 100% load test using the HeavyLoad utility, temps never exceeded 86 Celcius, and that's with Overclock on. Mounting was great, no issues, and no noise that I can hear. Great deal for an AIO.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 1, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Cools a Ryzen 7600x Easily
reviews.reviewText: Cooler was pretty easy to install. My motherboard has some big heatsinks, and I needed to squeeze the radiator in the case. It's quiet under 75% load. Once it hits 80/85% and up on the fans, you'll definitely hear it. On the upside, my Ryzen 5 7600x never goes past 86C (and that is stock. No Curve Optimizer, undervolting or anything).There's no real RGB lighting or anything, but the logo on the pump/sink lights up a sort of off-white. It looks good.Packaging was really nice, the radiator and fins were nice and straight and not bent. The fans, themselves are pretty nice. They don't look or feel cheap. I removed the SATA power adapter, the pump runs fine off the motherboard connector.If you look at this radiator and compare it to, say an Arctic, the Arctic radiator is noticeably thicker. It's something to consider, but for the price I paid and for the performance i'm receiving, i'm not complaining at all.EDIT (After a few months) I had to replace the fan y-splitter cable. I coiled it pretty tight and probably damaged it, one fan would spin up to 100% but the reported rpm would be low and the other fan would spin at the lower rpm. I think the splitter cable is fragile/stiff, and honestly I did some weird tricks to hide the cable in my case. Very good value cooler, and i'd buy ID Cooling products in the future.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 8, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Great fan for 7800x3d
reviews.reviewText: I got this because all the AIO's were super expensive, this is the best AIO for the money. It easily cools th 7800x3d with the fans it comes with, and you can easily replace the fans with some 3000 RPM noctua fans later down the line if you so choose too. reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 24, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Does the job
reviews.reviewText: I had one PC that was getting too loud with an air cooler. I haven’t had an air cooler in ages but it had such good reviews that I tried it out. Well, it turned out to be too noisy when you were in the room and it was putting out so much heat.i wanted a cheap water cooler and I replaced it with this. It seems to run great and was relatively easy to install (I have a small case which is not the fault of the product.) It’s quiet and the temps have been low. My only complaint is the LED on the pump. i wish there was some way I could disable it as my case is clear on one side.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on May 20, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Good enough for the price.
reviews.reviewText: This is my first AIO water cooler and it was very easy to install. It was cheaper than some heartsick/fans so why not. Works well and takes up considerably less space than my heat sink/fan combo I had. At first, I installed only 2 fans and my CPU (i7 12700) would reach 40-45 at idol. I didn’t want to up the fan speeds because I would start to hear them. So I put 2 more fans and sandwich the radiator between 4 fans. Now the temp at idol hovers around 37-40. Fans rpm less than 1000. I don’t OC or play any games that would max the CPU so I think this will be adequate. I stress tested the CPU with CPU-Z and it would max out at around 80. From what I’ve read in other reviews, the included thermal paste is terrible (understandable for the price) so I used my own Arctic Silver mx-4. Might as well just not include it since people will need to do it twice…Some people reported loud noises at start up but mine is totally quiet. Virtually zero noise at startup. Guess I don’t have air in mines? Some people reported problems with the screws but mine didn’t have that problem either. They give you only 8 long screws so I had to get myself 8 more to do the 4 fan sandwich. Go to Home Depot and get #6-32 1-1/4 inches if you want to do the same. They fit perfectly. I also got some #6 washers just in case they went too deep and hit the radiator. I don’t know if it would though without the washers.In any case, if you’re serious about OC or always max out your CPU with games, video renders or whatever, you might want to invest in a branded cooler. But this is perfectly fine for everyday computing and gaming. Gaming mostly uses the GPU anyway and rarely maxes out the CPU. Let’s just hope it doesn’t start leaking in a few years.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 8, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Easy to Install, And Customizable with your current fans
reviews.reviewText: Best thing about the product, is it’s cost effectiveness #1. It comes with thermal paste that most AIO companies don’t give you. Which saves you $7 already. Water cooler is compatible with other fans, if you already have your own RGB. Easy to install, and has several screws and mounts for different motherboard options.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 11, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars First attempt only had 3 of 4 standoffs needed, but once that was taken care of, worked great
reviews.reviewText: I was one of those "frequent returns"-- this cooler came with 3 of the 4 standoffs needed for the LGA 1700 install. Amazon shipped out a new one, I swiped the standoffs I needed and sent back the replacement, which I told them about.Once installed, the cooler was GREAT. Dropped temps in my case significantly, not just for the CPU, but for the graphics card as well, because it opened up airflow a lot compared to the bulky air cooler I'd tried first. I'm running a 13600kf, not the hottest card, but it can get pretty toasty on an air cooler. In NMS, it runs in the mid-40s, for example, with the water cooler. With the air cooler I was hitting TJ max in Cinebench, and the water cooler took me at least 15 degrees cooler than that.So be prepared for a little tomfoolery in the way of attention to detail, but once you get all the parts you need, this works great.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on January 12, 2024
reviews.reviewText: I have several AIOs from Corsair in my computers. I bought this AIO because I needed something cheaper and equally good. I was completely surprised by this model. Very easy to install and extremely quiet and effective in operation. No RGB, but I didn't need it in this computer, no monitor on the pump (I didn't need it either). However, they operate very quietly and keep the processor temperature low. AIO is not big. Only 280mm but very good. I use it to cool the Intel i7 12700K processor. I play a lot on this computer and I am very pleased with the quality and performance of this AIO. I highly recommend. You won't spend much money, and competing companies demand a lot of money for their AIOs. Why overpay?

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on November 19, 2023
reviews.reviewText: This cooler is excellent value for money. I've used it in an office machine shown in the photo as well as a mid range gaming machine running an i5 10400f paired with a GTX1660 Super and it's keeping the temperatures well within range even when you're really pushing the hardware hard! It's not the flashiest piece of kit but if you're looking for something that does it's job without fuss and presents great value then I would recommend this cooler.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on November 12, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: Works great on a AMD Ryzen 7 5800X3D
reviews.reviewText: Don't listen to the clueless noobs out there saying it does not keep your CPU cool, I am currently using this on my AMD Ryzen 7 5800X3D and my pc is like a fridge.
